Headlines.Author: Angel Gonzalez
Headlines.Headline: Noble Energy In Santiago Find, Increases Projected Galapagos Output

PARAGRAPH.#text: HOUSTON (Dow Jones)--Noble Energy Inc. NBL said Tuesday that it made the first oil discovery since deep-water drilling resumed in the U.S. Gulf of Mexico. The Houston-based company said that its Santiago exploration well met 60 feet of oil pay in a high-quality reservoir. Noble owns 23.25% of the prospect, which is part of the larger Galapagos project. BP PLC (BP, BP.LN) owns 46.5% and Red Willow Offshore LLC owns 20.25%. The Santiago prospect is located at a water depth of 6,500 feet. Including the Santiago prospect, the Galapagos project is estimated to contain 130 million barrels of oil equivalent, 75% of which are thought to be oil.

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Indonesia free-fall sparks Asia sell-off

PARAGRAPH.#text:
HONG KONG (AP) -- Spooked by a record fall in Indonesia's currency, stock
    markets across Southeast Asia dropped sharply Thursday as investors liquidated portfolios.
    
    
    Indonesia's rupiah plunged 26 percent and its stock market suffered a 12 percent drop--
    both one-day worsts -- while Singapore shares hit a 5-year low and Philippine shares a
    4-year low. 
    
    There was good news in South Korea, where the main share index rose 3.6 percent due to
    strong buying demand from foreign investors. Foreigners, now allowed under new laws to own
    up to 55 percent of listed South Korean companies, snapped up shares of Korea Electric
    Power Corp., LG Electronics Inc. and Daewoo Telecom Co. 
    
    And in Tokyo, the yen strengthened slightly against the U.S. dollar due to expectations
    that the Bank of Japan might intervene to support the currency while senior Finance
    Ministry official Eisuke Sakakibara visits Washington this week. After climbing above 134
    yen early this week, to its highest level in more than 5 1/2 years, the dollar retreated
    to 133.01. 
    
    Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange were little changed. The Nikkei index fell 0.06 percent
    to 15,019.18.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Indonesia free-fall sparks Asia sell-off

Headlines.Headline: Seagate to report second quarter loss

#text:
Seagate
    Technology

said it will report a "substantial loss from operations" for the
    second fiscal quarter. The disk drive maker blamed pricing pressure and "weakness in
    demand for its disc drives" for the disappointment. Analysts had expected the company
    to earn 3 cents a share. Seagate said revenues from drive operations are expected to be
    $1.5 billion for the quarter while total revenues are estimated at $1.65 billion. The
    Scotts Valley, Calif.-based company will take restructuring charges of $250 million in the
    quarter and an additional $50 million in its third fiscal quarter. The company also said
    it will take unspecified charges for inventory write-downs and other one-time charges.
    Seagate shares fell 1 1/4 to 20 5/8. The company made the announcement after the market
    closed. Seagate missed earnings estimates last quarter as well.
